<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-07-15T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-07-15T11:00:00-05:00" n="534" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d534">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/2867: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-07-15T12:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">July 15,
                                            1920—noon</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                            <p>742. Your 1057, July 13, 7 p.m.</p>
                            <p>This Government did not feel warranted in communicating to the
                                Japanese Government the British and French Government’s approval of
                                the Lamont-Kajiwara letters<note n="44" xml:id="d534fn44"><hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_555">pp.
                                    555</ref>, <ref target="#pg_556">556</ref>.</note> but will be
                                glad to communicate <pb facs="0650" n="552" xml:id="pg_552"/> such
                                approval if the British and French Governments will authorize it so
                                to do and will instruct their representatives at Tokyo to that
                                effect.</p>
                            <p>Repeat to Paris as number 1252.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>